725792f-a.text:
111th Street, south from 44th Avenue, across the Long Island Railroad tracks. The area on the left, which stretches along the east side of 111th Street, is part of the Corona dumps and later became Flushing Meadow Park where the New York
World's Fair of 1939-40 was held.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  1923

725791f-a.text:
111th Street, east side, at 44th Avenue, showing a shingled house, formely a roadhouse, this side of the Long Island Railroad
tracks.
Eugene L. Arbruster Collection  1923

726624f-a.text:
Flushing Meadow Park (Queens): The western extremity of the New York World's Fair, looking south on 111th Street (right) from 45th Avenue, and showing construction operations on various buildings. Obstructed by the mound of earth is the skeleton of the Railroads Building; beyond that is the Chrysler Bui'ding and the
Corona gates of the Fair grounds.
View 2 shows the same area, when completed.
View 1: November 2, 1936
View 2: June 23, 1940
P. L. Sperr
